The Conservationof Massin Chemical Reactions 	  Both the numbers of each type of atom and the mass are conserved during chemical reactions. An examination of a properly balanced equation will demonstrate that mass is conserved. Consider the following reaction. 
Fe( H)3 + 3  Na O3 	  You should demonstrate that this equation is balanced by counting the number of each type of atom on each side of the equation. We can also demonstrate that mass is conserved in this reaction by determining the total mass on the two sides of the equation. 
Reactant Side Mass 	  Total mass for reactants = 241.9 daltons + 120. daltons = 361.9 daltons 
Product Side Mass 	  Total mass for products = 106.9 daltons + 255 daltons = 361.9 daltons. As you can see, both number of atom types and mass are conserved during chemical reactions. A group of 20 objects stacked in different ways will still have the same total mass no matter how you stack them. 
