Enthalpy 	  • Define and understand enthalpy of reaction. • Calculate the enthalpy of reaction using ∆Hrxn = ∆Hproducts ∆Hreactants. • Describe, interpret, and draw potential energy diagrams. • Define and understand ∆Hf. • Define Hess’s Law. • Calculate ∆Hrxn using Hess’s Law. 
Introduction 	  The change in enthalpy for a reaction can be determined by three methods. First, the enthalpy of the reaction is found by finding the difference between the enthalpies of the products and reactants in the lab using a calorimeter. Second, the change in enthalpy for a reaction can also be calculated using the heats of formation of all the reactants and products. Thirdly, the change in enthalpy can be calculated using the mathematical application of Hess's Law. 
The Energy Contentofa System 	  Enthalpy has been defined previously as the measure of the total internal energy of a system. The difference between the enthalpy of the reactants and the enthalpy of the products is called the change in enthalpy. When reactions take place in an open system, such as a beaker, or a container on a counter, the pressure in the system is constant because the pressure is the atmospheric pressure in the room. The change in enthalpy for reactions occurring under constant pressure is also called the ΔH or heat of reaction. ∆Hrxn= ∆Hproducts ∆Hreactants Remember that for an endothermic reaction, the value of ∆H is positive, therefore the ∆Hproducts must be greater than ∆Hreactants. To illustrate this, look at Figure 1. (Created by: Therese Forsythe, License: CC-BY-SA) In Figure 1, the enthalpy of the reactants is lower than the energy of the products. Therefore, energy must be input into the reaction and the value of the ∆H will be positive. The opposite is true for exothermic reactions. For exothermic reactions the value of ∆H is negative and therefore the enthalpy of the products must be less than enthalpy of the reactants. Notice that for Figure 2, the energy of the reactants is higher than the energy of the products. Therefore the value of the ∆H will be negative. (Created by: Therese Forsythe, License: CC-BY-SA) The figures represented are referred to as potentialenergydiagrams. They are called this because they indicate the potential energy of the reactants and the products. Sample question: Using the diagram below, answer questions (a) through (d). (a) Which letter represents the activation energy for the reaction? What is its value? (b) Which letter represents the change in enthalpy of the reaction or the ∆H? What is its value? (c) Is the reaction endothermic or exothermic? How can you tell? (d) What does the letter (e) represent? Solution: (a) The activation energy is represented by letter (d). It has a value of 250 – 100 = 150 kJ. (b) The enthalpy change (∆H) is represented by letter (c). It has a value of 50 – 100 = -50 kJ. (c) The reaction is exothermic because ∆H is negative and the products are lower than the reactants on the potential energy diagram. (d) Letter e represents the activation energy for the reverse reaction. 
Enthalpyof Formation 	  A formation reaction is a reaction in which exactly one mole of a product is formed from its elements. The enthalpyofformation, ∆Hf, is the energy required to form one mole of a substance from its constituent elements at standard temperature and pressure. Equation 1 represents the ∆Hf for the formation of one mole of NH3(g). N2(g) + H2(g) NH3(g) ∆Hf = -46.1 kJ/mol (Equation 1) We can find these values for enthalpies of formation using a table of standard molar enthalpies found in the CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics, online, or in most chemistry textbooks. The values found in these sources are the values of ∆Hf or the enthalpy of formation. In Equation 1, exactly one mole of ammonia is formed from its elements and that qualifies the reaction as a formation reaction and its ΔH to be a ΔHf. Equation 2 does not qualify to be a formation reaction. ∆Hf = -571.6 kJ (Equation 2) The enthalpy of formation is for the formation of one mole of a substance from its elements. Equation 2 shows the formation of two moles of water and therefore does not represent ∆Hf. In order to represent the ∆Hf for water, we must divide Equation 2 by two. H2(g) + ½ O2(g) H2O(L) ∆Hf = -285.8 kJ (Equation 3) If we were to reverse this reaction, look at what would happen to the value of ∆H. H2O(L) H2(g) + ½ O2(g) ∆H = 285.8 kJ (Equation 4) Equation 4 no longer represents the heat of formation because the equation represents a decomposition reaction. However, look at the value of ∆H. Since the equation was reversed, the sign of the value of ∆H was also reversed. It 285.8 kJ was given when one mole of water formed from its elements, then to decompose that mole of water back into its elements, an input of 285.8 kJ is required. The ΔH for the forward reaction will be exactly the opposite of the ΔH for the reverse reaction. You can use the values of ∆Hf found in the table of standard heats of formation to find the enthalpy of a reaction (or ∆Hrxn}). Consider the following equation. 
