Higher Temperature Favors More Entropy 	  When the temperature of a substance is increases, the molecules have greater average kinetic energy and therefore move around with greater velocity. The greater velocity of the particles means they collide more often and with greater force. The greater force of the collisions cause the molecules to spread further apart and therefore, they will have greater entropy. Increasing the temperature of a system favors the tendency toward greater randomness or maximum entropy. 
